<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-409-588  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 409 588.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>CAD-CAM International  March 1990 v9 n3 p40(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Technology in step with tradition. (includes related article oncomputer aided patterns)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Palframan, Diane.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>British United Shoe Machinery (BU) is the UK's leading producer ofshoe making machinery, and builds products ranging from standalonemachines to complete computer-controlled factories.andP;  BU employs astaff of 750, has a turnover of 32.5 million pounds sterling, andspends about a million pounds sterling yearly on new equipment andcomputer systems.andP;  The company blends old and new, implementingnew technology that supports productivity and growth as well asits market leadership.andP;  BU's CAD system includes an IBM 4341mainframe connected to 14 workstations running Cadam mechanicalengineering software, and is used for such tasks as new productdesign and engineering.andP;  The company also uses a Perkin Elmercomputer for product research and analysis, and Compaq computersfor printed circuit board design.andP;  BU has acquired an ICL 3900mainframe that runs Orma, ICL's sales and order entry program,along with financial applications from MGB Ledger.andP;  On the shopfloor, BU employs a flexible manufacturing system (FMS) that hasimproved the quality of parts and reduced work in progress.andP;  Thecompany also uses Crispin, a CAD system capable of shoe stylingand grading.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   British United Shoe Machinery (automation).andO;Topic:     Case StudyManufacturersUnited KingdomCAD-CAMComputer SystemsManagement of EDPSystem DesignImplementationStrategic Planning.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>